8. Draw the hierarchy of processes created by the code below, including the parent process:
   for(i=0; i<3; i++) {
       fork();
       execlp("ls", "ls", "/", NULL);
   }
   -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Answer:
   The hierarchy structure forms a master parent process branch that forks exactly 
   3 independent children before exiting:
   
          Parent (i=0)
             |
       +-----+-----+
       |           |
   Parent(i=1)   Child1 (Executes 'ls' instantly and terminates)
       |
   +---+---+
   |       |
   ...   Child2 (Executes 'ls' instantly and terminates)
   
   Justification: When fork() triggers, the newly created child process immediately 
   moves to the next instruction line and executes 'execlp()'. This completely 
   overwrites the child's memory image with the 'ls' program binary. Consequently, 
   the child terminates and never loops. Only the original master parent process 
   survives to loop and call fork() up to 3 times. Total processes: 1 parent + 3 children.


9. Draw the hierarchy of processes created by the code below, including the parent process:
   for(i=0; i<3; i++) {
       if(fork() > 0) {
           wait(0);
           wait(0);
           exit(0);
       }
   }
   -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
   Answer:
   The process generation hierarchy forms a single linear chain of descent:
   Parent -> Child1 -> Child2 -> Child3
   
   Justification: At loop iteration index i=0, the parent calls fork(). The parent 
   receives a positive child PID return value, making 'fork() > 0' evaluate to True. 
   It enters the conditional block, waits for its child, and exits. Meanwhile, 
   Child1 receives a 0 return status, bypasses the conditional block, and loops 
   to index i=1 to spawn Child2. This sequential processing model creates a 
   straight linear tree structure.


10. Explain why the file descriptor returned by popen must be closed with pclose instead of fclose.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    The popen() standard library routine constructs an internal process engine by 
    forking a child shell and running an explicit data pipeline channel. While a standard 
    fclose() call only flushes and tears down the basic runtime memory stream buffer, 
    pclose() also calls waitpid() on the hidden child process. This captures its exit 
    status code and prevents it from turning into a system zombie process.


11. Give an advantage and a disadvantage of the First Fit placement policy versus the Worst-Fit placing policy.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    - Advantage: First Fit is computationally faster because it allocates the very 
      first memory block it finds that is large enough, rather than searching the 
      entire global memory block list.
    - Disadvantage: It causes high rates of external fragmentation near the head 
      of the memory list, creating small, unusable memory holes over time.


12. Give an example of distinct values greater than 0 for T, N1, N2, and N3 for which the program below finishes execution:
    pthread_barrier_t b1, b2;
    void* f1(void* a) { pthread_barrier_wait(&b1); return NULL; }
    void* f2(void* a) { pthread_barrier_wait(&b2); return NULL; }
    int main() {
        int i; pthread_t t[T][2];
        pthread_barrier_init(&b1, NULL, N1);
        pthread_barrier_init(&b2, NULL, N2);
        for(i=0; i<T; i++) {
            pthread_create(&t[i][0], NULL, f1, NULL);
            pthread_create(&t[i][1], NULL, f2, NULL);
        }
        for(i=0; i<T; i++) {
            pthread_join(t[i][0], NULL); pthread_join(t[i][1], NULL);
        }
        pthread_barrier_destroy(&b1); pthread_barrier_destroy(&b2);
        return NULL;
    }
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    Valid values: T = 4, N1 = 4, N2 = 4, N3 = 1 (N3 can be any positive value).
    
    Justification: The program loop generates exactly T instances of the f1 thread 
    and T instances of the f2 thread. To ensure the barriers release successfully and 
    do not deadlock execution, the thread arrival threshold requirements (N1 and N2) 
    must equal or evenly divide the total count of running worker threads T.


13. Give five GREP commands that display all the lines in a file that contain letter "a" uppercase or lowercase.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
