17. Give three regular expressions that match any non-negative number multiple of 5.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    1. ^(0|[1-9][0-9]*[05])$
    2. ^[0-9]*[05]$
    3. ^([05]|[1-9][0-9]*0|[1-9][0-9]*5)$


18. Give three ways of finding the size of a file on the Linux command line.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    1. wc -c file.txt
    2. stat -c %s file.txt
    3. ls -l file.txt | awk '{print $5}'


19. Give three GREP commands that display the lines of a file which consist exclusively of a non-empty sequence of alternating letters and digits (e.g., a0g or 1r5m).
    ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Answer:
    1. grep -E "^([a-zA-Z]([0-9][a-zA-Z])*|[0-9]([a-zA-Z][0-9])*)[0-9]?$" file.txt
    2. grep -E -i "^([a-z]([0-9][a-z])*|[0-9]([a-z][0-9])*)[0-9]?$" file.txt
    3. grep -E "^([A-Za-z][0-9])*[A-Za-z]?$|^([0-9][A-Za-z])*[0-9]?$" file.txt


20. Give a regular expression that matches any even-length sequence of lower-case words separated by spaces, if for each word its length and its position in the sequence are either both odd or both even. The words are counted starting with 1. (Ex: the 5th word must have odd length and the 16th word must have even length).
